<p class="drop-cap">On July 16, 1054, Cardinal Humbert of Silva Candida strode into the Hagia Sophia during the Saturday afternoon liturgy and placed a papal bull of excommunication on the high altar. Then he walked out. Patriarch Michael Cerularius of Constantinople picked it up, read it, and excommunicated Humbert right back.</p>

<p>That is the popular version: one dramatic afternoon, two stubborn men, and Christianity split in half. The reality is messier, slower, and more instructive. The "Great Schism" was not a single event. It was a process that took centuries, and in some ways it is still unfolding.</p>

<h2>What Actually Happened in 1054</h2>

<p>Humbert was in Constantinople on a diplomatic mission from Pope Leo IX. The relationship between Rome and Constantinople had been deteriorating for decades over multiple issues: jurisdictional disputes in southern Italy, liturgical differences, and the <em>filioque</em> controversy. When Pope Leo died during Humbert's visit, the cardinal's authority to act on papal behalf became legally questionable.</p>

<p>Humbert's bull excommunicated Cerularius and his supporters. Cerularius's synod excommunicated Humbert and the other legates. Neither side excommunicated the other's entire church. The mutual excommunications were personal and limited. Most Christians in both East and West barely noticed.</p>

<p>For decades afterward, communion between Rome and Constantinople continued in many places. Pilgrims traveled freely. Clergy concelebrated. The "schism of 1054" became a fixed date in textbooks only much later, when historians needed a clean turning point for a story that resists one.</p>

