<h2>An Irenic Conclusion</h2>

<p>Assigning blame for the schism is easy. Too easy. Both sides contributed. Both sides have legitimate grievances and legitimate theological positions. The point is not to win the argument but to heal the wound.</p>

<p>The Eastern Christian who encounters the West with curiosity rather than defensiveness will find genuine holiness, serious theology, and a deep love of Christ. The Western Christian who encounters the East will find the same. The tragedy of the schism is not that one side was right and the other wrong. The tragedy is that the Body of Christ was torn, and the tearing diminished both halves.</p>

<p>Healing is not the same as pretending the differences don't exist. They do, and they matter. But the differences are best addressed within a relationship of mutual respect and shared prayer. The schism began with men walking away from each other. It can only end with men walking toward each other.</p>

<h2>Further Reading</h2>

<p>For a balanced overview, see Kallistos Ware's <em>The Orthodox Church</em> (chapters on the estrangement). Steven Runciman's <em>The Eastern Schism</em> remains the classic historical treatment. For the 1204 disaster, Jonathan Phillips's <em>The Fourth Crusade and the Sack of Constantinople</em> is gripping and well-documented. On the theological dialogue since Vatican II, see the joint statements published by the North American Orthodox-Catholic Theological Consultation.</p>

